      "\n   - Similarly for `|A| < 4`, the condition is vacuously true, and we can always take `S = ∅`, so any `c` is fine. \n   - Now take `A` with `|A| ≥ 4`. But we need that for *every* subset `B ⊆ A` with `|B| = 4`, `|B - B| = 11`. \n\n   Now, we need to find if there exists any finite set `A ⊆ ℝ` with `|A| ≥ 4` such that every 4-element subset `B` satisfies `|B - B| = 11`. \n\n   - Suppose `A` is such a set. Let `B ⊆ A` be any 4-element subset. Then `B - B` is the set of differences `x - y` for `x, y ∈ B`. Generally, for 4 points in `ℝ`, `|B - B| = 7` if `B` is in arithmetic progression, but it can be larger if not (up to `4 choose 2 + 4 choose 2 = 12`, but usually less due to overlaps). So to get `11`, some differences must coincide in a specific way. \n\n   - Actually, it is not clear if such sets exist, but if they don't, then the condition is vacuously true for all finite sets `A`, and every `c ∈ ℝ` is admissible, including all `c > 1/2`.\n\n   - But perhaps it is not vacuously true because some sets do satisfy the condition. Let's think:\n     - Take `A = {0, 1, 2, 4}`. Then `B = A` is the only 4-element subset, and `B - B = {-4, -3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3, 4}` (size 9 ≠ 11). \n     - Take `A = {0, 1, 3, 5}`. Then `B - B = {-5, -3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3, 5}` (size 9 again).\n     - Maybe no 4-element subset `B` of reals has `|B - B| = 11`. But this would mean that no `|A| ≥ 4` satisfies the condition, hence the only `A` that satisfy it are those with `|A| < 4`.\n\n   But in that case, the hypothesis in `IsAdmissible c` is always false for `A` with `|A| ≥ 4`, and vacuously true otherwise. So for any `c`, the implication holds. Therefore, `{c | IsAdmissible c} = ℝ`, and `sSup ℝ = +∞`. But in Lean, `sSup_univ` is `+∞` for `ℝ`, and `1/2 < +∞` is true.\n\n   However, in Lean, `sSup` is the least upper bound in the extended real numbers, and Lean's `sSup_univ_real` is indeed `+∞`. So `sSup {c | IsAdmissible c} = sSup ℝ = +∞`, and `1/2 < +∞` is true.\n\n   But I think that in Lean, `ℝ` does not have `+∞`, and `sSup` for `ℝ` is only defined if the set is nonempty and bounded above. So perhaps `{c | IsAdmissible c}` is actually `∅` if no conditions are met, and then `sSup ∅ = -∞` in Lean? But that would not make sense. Actually, Lean requires that `sSup s` exists only if `s` is bounded above, otherwise it is junk.\n\n   But perhaps in Lean, `{c | IsAdmissible c}` is all of `ℝ`, and so it is not bounded above, and then Lean considers `sSup` to be junk. \n\n   This is confusing because the theorem statement is trying to take `sSup` of a set that may not be bounded above. \n\n   Looking back at the Lean code: the set is `{c : ℝ | IsAdmissible c}`. So perhaps if no set `A` satisfies the condition, then every `c` is admissible. Indeed, if for all finite `A`, the condition `∀ B ⊆ A, |B| = 4 → |B - B| = 11` is false, then the implication is vacuously true. \n\n   But is there any finite `A` of size ≥ 4 that satisfies this condition? \n\n   Let me try to find one:\n   - Take `A = {0, 1, r, r+1}` for some real number `r`. Then `B = A` has `B - B = {-1, 0, 1} ∪ {r - (r + 1), r - 1, etc.}`. \n   - Hmm, not obvious. Maybe take `A = {1, 2, 3, 4}`. `B - B` has `{-3, ..., 3}`, size 7.\n   - Take `A = {0, 1, 2, 4}`: `B - B = {-4, -3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3, 4}`, size 9.\n   - Take `A = {0, 1, 3, 7}`: `B - B = {-7, -6, -4, -3, -1, 0, 1, 3, 4, 6, 7}`, size 11. \n\n   Ah! So `A = {0, 1, 3, 7}` is such that `B = A` (the only subset of size 4) has `|B - B| = 11`. \n\n   So the condition in `IsAdmissible c` is not vacuously true. \n\n   But this example already shows that there exists at least one finite set `A` of size 4 for which `∀ B ⊆ A, |B| = 4 → |B - B| = 11`. \n\n   Therefore, in order for a `c` to be admissible, when we take `A = {0, 1, 3, 7}`, we need to find a Sidon subset `S ⊆ A` with `c * 4 ≤ |S|` (`A.ncard = 4`). \n\n   We have `S` can be any subset of `A`, and `S` is Sidon if all pairwise sums are distinct. So `A` itself is not Sidon because, e.g., `1 + 3 = 0 + 4`, but we have no `4`. Hmm. \n\n   No: `{0, 1, 3, 7}`: The pairwise sums are `1, 3, 7, 4, 8, 10`, all distinct. So it is actually a Sidon set!\n\n   So the whole set `S = A = {0, 1, 3, 7}` is a Sidon subset of itself. Then for `c` to be admissible, we need `c * 4 ≤ 4`, so `c ≤ 1`. \n\n   But perhaps there are other `A` with stronger conditions. \n\n   The problem is asking for the supremum of all `c` such that for EVERY finite set `A`, if every 4-subset `B` of `A` has `|B - B| = 11`, then `A` contains a Sidon subset of size `≥ c |A|`.\n\n   So `c = 1` is admissible because we can always take `S` to be the entire set `A`, but only if `A` is Sidon. \n\n   But maybe `A` is not Sidon. \n\n   Wait, in the case `A = {0, 1, 3, 7}`, it is Sidon, so taking `S = A` is okay. \n\n   What if we had another example? \n\n   Alternatively, is there an `A` where we cannot take `S = A`? \n\n   Let me try `A = {0, 1, 3, 7, x}`. Now, any 4-subset `B` of `A` must have `|B - B| = 11`. \n\n   - If `x = 2`, take `B = {0, 1, 2, 3}`: `B - B = {-3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3}`, size 7 ≠ 11. So invalid. \n   - If `x = 4`, take `B = {1, 3, 4, 7}`: `B - B = {-6, -3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 6}`, size 10 ≠ 11. \n   - If `x = 5`, take `B = {0, 1, 3, 5}`: `B - B = {-5, -3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3, 5}`, size",
