      "\n  - This happens because there are no finite subsets `A ⊆ ℝ` where every 4-element subset `B` has `(B - B).ncard = 11`. \n  - For example, if `A` has fewer than 4 elements, no 4-element subsets exist (vacuous truth), but `A.ncard = 0` makes `c * A.ncard = 0` and any `S = ∅` works (`IsSidon ∅` holds trivially).\n  - If `A` has ≥ 4 elements, it is unclear if any such `A` exists, but we might not need it because Lean's `sSup` on empty sets is `-∞`, but our set is not empty since `c = 0` is trivially admissible (take `S = ∅`).\n\nBut this approach seems complicated. A better approach is to realize that if there exists *any* `c > 1/2` that is admissible, then `sSup {c | ...} ≥ c > 1/2`. However, constructed examples (like arithmetic progressions) do not satisfy the condition because they have repeated differences. \n\nA simpler observation is that `A = ∅` is a finite set. The condition is vacuously true (no subsets `B` with `ncard = 4` exist). Now for `c = 0`, we have `S = ∅ ⊆ A`, which is Sidon and `0 * 0 ≤ 0`. Thus, `0` is admissible, so `{c | ...}` is non-empty. But this doesn't directly help. \n\nHere’s the critical point: no finite set `A ⊆ ℝ` with `A.ncard ≥ 4` can satisfy the condition that *every* 4-element subset `B` has `(B - B).ncard = 11`. Why? \n- For any 4-element subset `B = {a, b, c, d}`, `B - B` has size at most `4 * 3 + 1 = 13` (since there are at most 12 ordered pairs `(x, y)` with `x ≠ y`, and `(x, x)` gives 0). \n  - Actually, the maximum size is `C(4,2) + C(4,2) + 1 = 6 + 6 + 1 = 13` (differences of the form `a_i - a_j` and `a_j - a_i` are the same, but for `a_i - a_i = 0`). \n  - But to have `|B - B| = 11`, we must have exactly 11 distinct differences, which is possible if some of the 12 possible non-zero differences coincide.\n  - For example, an arithmetic progression `B = {1, 2, 3, 4}` has `B - B = {-3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3}` of size 7, not 11.\n  - Another example: `B = {1, 2, 4, 8}` has differences `1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 7, 8` (plus negatives and zero), giving `B - B` of size 13, not 11.\n  - It turns out that it’s hard to get exactly 11 distinct differences. \n  - However, we need a combinatorial argument that for all `B`, `|B - B| ≠ 11`. \n\nBut perhaps such `A` exist, and our task is to prove that `sSup {c | ...} > 1/2`. \n\nHowever, perhaps `{c | ...}` contains all real numbers because no finite `A` with `A.ncard ≥ 4` exists such that all its 4-element subsets `B` satisfy `(B - B).ncard = 11`. \n\nIs that true? \n\nLet me think differently: suppose that no finite `A ⊆ ℝ` with `A.ncard ≥ 4` satisfies the condition that every 4-element subset `B` has `(B - B).ncard = 11`. Then:\n\n1. If `A.ncard < 4`: The condition is vacuously true. \n   - For `c` to be admissible, for `A`, there must exist a Sidon subset `S ⊆ A` with `c * |A| ≤ |S|`. \n   - We can always take `S = ∅`, so `c * |A| ≤ 0`. If `c ≤ 0`, `c * |A| ≤ 0` is satisfied (`|A| ≥ 0`). So, `c = 0` is admissible, but `c = 1` may not be if `A = {a}` because `1 * 1 ≤ 0` is false. \n\nBut perhaps no `A` with `|A| ≥ 4` satisfies the condition. \n\nAlternatively, perhaps there exists a special `A`, e.g., `A = {0, 1, 3, 6, 10}` (triangular numbers) or some Sidon set, where the condition is satisfied, but `|B - B| = 11` for all 4-element subsets `B`. \n\nBut it seems that `|B - B| = 11` cannot happen for any 4-element `B`, because for `B = {a, b, c, d}`, we have: \n`B - B = {a - a, a - b, a - c, a - d, b - a, b - b, b - c, b - d, c - a, c - b, c - c, c - d, d - a, d - b, d - c, d - d} = {0} ∪ {a - b, a - c, a - d, b - c, b - d, c - d} ∪ {b - a, c - a, d - a, c - b, d - b, d - c}`. \nBut actually, this equals `{0} ∪ {a - b, a - c, a - d, b - c, b - d, c - d} ∪ {-(a - b), -(a - c), ...}`, so `|B - B| = 1 + 2 * number_of_distinct_nonzero_differences`. \n\nBut for 4 elements, the number of distinct nonzero differences can range from `C(4,2) = 6` (if all differences are distinct, e.g., `B = {0, 1, 3, 6}`, with differences `1, 3, 6, 2, 5, 3`; here `B - B = {-5, -3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3, 5}`, size 9) to fewer if some differences coincide. \n\nIt turns out that 11 is not achievable: \n- `1 + 2 * k = 11 ⇒ k = 5`, but the number of distinct nonzero differences is an integer between `3` (e.g., `B = {0, 1, 2, 3}` with differences `1, 2, 3, 1, 2, 1`) and `6`, so `k = 5` is possible if 5 of the 6 differences are distinct. \n  - Try `B = {0, 1, 2, 4}`: differences are `1, 2, 4, 1, 3, 2`. Nonzero distinct differences: `1, 2, 3, 4` (4 of them). Then `B - B = {-4, -3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3, 4}` (9 elements). \n  - Try `B = {0, 1, 3, 6}`: differences `1, 3, 6, 2, 5, 3`. Distinct: `1, 2, 3, 5, 6` (5 of them). Then `B - B` contains `0, ±1, ±2, ±3, ±5, ±6` (`11` elements)? Wait:\n    - `B - B = { -6, -5, -3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3, 5, 6 }` (excluding duplicates). That is `11` elements! \n\nYes! The set `{0, 1, 3, 6}` has `(B - B).ncard = 11`. \n\nThis means that if `A` is the set `{0, 1, 3, 6, x}`, we can have subsets `B = {0, 1, 3, 6}` with `(B - B).ncard = 11`, but another subset `B' = {0, 1, 3, x}` would impose a condition on `(B' - B').ncard`. \n\nHowever, in Lean, the condition is that **for every subset `B` of size `4`, `(B - B).ncard = 11`**. \n\nThus, `A = {0, 1, 3, 6}` is invalid because it doesn't have `A.ncard ≥ 4` (wait no, it has `A.ncard = 4`), but then the condition is that for `B = A`, `(B - B).ncard = 11`, which is true. \nThus, for `A = {0, 1, 3, 6}`, it satisfies the condition of `IsAdmissible c` because the only `B` is `A` itself. \n\nNow, what is its Sidon subset `S` of size `≥ c * 4`? \n\n`A = {0, 1, 3, 6}` is not Sidon because `1 - 0 = 3 - 2`, but there no `2`. Wait no: `A` is `{0, 1, 3, 6}`. The condition for Sidon is that all differences are distinct. \n\nLet me compute all differences: \n`1 - 0 = 1`, `3 - 0 = 3`, `6 - 0 = 6`, \n`3 - 1 = 2`, `6 - 1 = 5`, \n`6 - 3 = 3`. \nOops, `3 - 0 = 3` and `6 - 3 = 3`, so `A` is not Sidon. \n\nBut the problem requires that for `A`, there exists `S ⊆ A` that is Sidon with `c * 4 ≤ |S|`. \