      "such a `c`:\n\nSuppose we take `c = 1`. \n\nWe need to check if it is admissible, i.e., for any finite `A`, if all subsets of size `4` have `|B - B| = 11`, then there is a Sidon subset `S ⊆ A` with `1 * |A| ≤ |S|`, i.e., `S = A` must be Sidon. \n\nBut this is not true: take `A = {0, 1, 4, 9}` union `{100}`. Then subsets of size `4` will either be `{0, 1, 4, 9}` (as above, `|A - A| = 11`) or `{1, 4, 9, 100}`, etc. \n\nBut `{1, 4, 9, 100} - {1, 4, 9, 100}` will have `(100 - 1) = 99` and many other differences; it will have more than `11` elements. \n\nHmm, perhaps not a good example because the subset `{1, 4, 9, 100}` doesn't satisfy `|B - B| = 11`.\n\nIn fact, perhaps no such set `A` of size `5` exists where *every* subset of size `4` has `|B - B| = 11`. \n\nAlternatively, perhaps `A` cannot have size `≥ 4`, because if you take `A` with `5` elements, then some subsets of size `4` will have `|B - B|` not equal to `11`. \n\nBut we need to find at least one set `A` with subsets of size `4` and `|B - B| = 11`, like `A = {0, 1, 4, 9}`. \n\nThen perhaps `c = 1` works for this `A` because `A` is Sidon. \n\nBut for another set like `A' = {0, 1, 4, 9, x}`, it is unclear whether the subsets of size `4` have `|B - B| = 11`, and even then, it is unclear whether `A'` is Sidon. \n\nThis approach is getting too complicated. \n\nAlternatively, perhaps in Lean, we can take `c = 1`, and argue that if `A` is a set with the condition (for every subset `B` of size `4`, `|B - B| = 11`), then either `A` has size `< 4` (in which case `S = A` is trivially Sidon and `1 * |A| ≤ |A|`), or `A` has size `≥ 4`, in which case... but it's not necessarily Sidon, so perhaps this is false.\n\nAnother idea: perhaps `c = 0` is the only admissible number. \n\nSuppose we try `c = 1`. Take `A = {0, 1, 4, 9}`. Then",
